The directory contains an example of oversampled inverter.

What do we mean by oversampling?

Let's say the model runs at 10us and that you drive it in HIL from Counting Digital Inputs (CDI) sampled at 10 ns (so 1000 faster sampling)

These CDI actually counts the number of 10ns tics between gate transitions, providing an average of the Logical 1 time at 10us (the inverter sampling time).

The technique is simple: for 10 us time steps with transitions, the inverter outputs voltage is set to the average voltage for this time step. 

This is well explained in a series of papers from Seimens using dSPACE from 1999. 
P. Terwiesch, T. Keller and E. Scheiben, "Rail vehicle control system integration testing using digital hardware-in-the-loop simulation," in IEEE Transactions on Control Systems Technology, vol. 7, no. 3, pp. 352-362, May 1999 
